Tools and machines. 
📄 
I’ve recently been introduced to the riso machine. I’d seen loads of brilliant riso prints from different illustrators so I was very excited to try it out myself. I liked some of the results I got. And I really like the way the colours lay over each other. But I’m not in love with process of standing in front of the riso machine and pressing buttons. It all feels a bit unromantic! 
📄 
But the process of making a load of risograph prints has taught me so much. I’ve been painting, but trying to paint in layers, as if I’m a risograph machine! I’m enjoying this technique (more romantic! 😂) and maybe I’ll return to the riso machine again at some point. 
📄 
You can see some of my riso results in stories, as well as some of the tools and machines that I use on a daily basis.

Lots of people were asking me about the 3 materials drawing challenge in Saturday’s “ask me anything”. In case you missed it, here you go….
☀️ 
What is the 3 materials challenge? 
The 3 materials drawing challenge was started by @kathryn_boyt a couple of years ago. I joined in for the first time last summer. It’s definitely the Instagram challenge that I’ve enjoyed the most. It made me think a lot more about colour and tone and light, and I learnt loads about how different materials respond to each other. Last year I took part in the challenge for 38 consecutive days. This time I plan to do 100, but you could do as many days as you like. 
☀️ 
What are the rules? 
(These are the rules that I will try to follow, but that I will also enjoy breaking!) 
✏️ Draw from life every day. 
✏️ Use only 3 materials for each drawing. They can be different materials each day…or not! E.g One yellow bingo dabber, One turquoise Neocolour II and one Payne’s Grey Derwent Inktense. 
✏️ Spend no more than 30 mins on each drawing. 
☀️ 
I’m starting on 5th May! 
☀️ 
Next week I’ll post my top tips for the challenge! 
.

This week is Refugee Week and the theme this year is “compassion”. 
💙
Over a few weeks last year, I had the pleasure of drawing at a clothes bank that helps to provide clothes for refugees and asylum seekers. This place provides so much more than that. In my drawings I tried to capture the care that goes into organising and sorting the clothes, as well as the tender conversations between the volunteers and the people using the clothes bank. This place perfectly sums up “compassion”. I hope that shows in my drawings. 
💙
I’m looking forward to returning to the clothes bank soon, to hang some of these drawings in their walls, and to do some more drawing. 
.

Day 48/100
I had a good time experimenting with a couple of things yesterday. 
✂️ 
Image 1 (neon): I’ve been meaning to try drawing at home from a location drawing for a while. I really enjoyed working on this, taking my time over certain areas and rethinking the composition.  Next time I’ll adapt the drawing more and perhaps add in imagined characters. I’m going to try drawing the same thing from memory immediately after drawing on location too. 
Image 2 (yellow and purple): Years ago I always worked in collage and I wanted to experiment with it on location. I drew the takeaway first and then drew figures passing by whilst I was there. I stuck them on at home. I’m not in love with the drawing but it was good fun and definitely something I’ll try again.
